<HL>
   Circle Express Founder
   Gets Three-Year Term
   On Conspiracy Charge
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   CEXX
</CO>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   INDIANAPOLIS -- The founder and former chief executive of
Circle Express Inc. was sentenced to three years in prison
and fined $250,000 after pleading guilty to conspiring to
provide false statements to the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   Arthur L. Belford, who left the trucking concern in 1989,
also agreed to surrender the Circle Express shares held by
him and his family and to make some restitution to
bondholders and shareholders.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Belford was the subject of a probe by the Federal
Bureau of Investigation. He was accused of using a company
condominium and airplane for personal purposes and of
agreeing to misrepresent the company's financial condition in
annual and quarterly reports.
   The trucking concern is under new management.
</TEXT>
